article.description:
Ray Allen scored 25 points to help the Seattle
SuperSonics beat the short-handed Philadelphia 76ers 102-98 on
Thursday night.
article.headline: Allen scores 25 as Sonics beat short-handed Sixers
article.linkText: Allen scores 25 as Sonics beat short-handed Sixers
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- SuperSonics guard Earl Watson was relieved that the Philadelphia 76ers were playing without his idol -- injured guard Allen Iverson. Led by Watson's defense and Ray Allen's 26 points, Seattle rallied from a 15-point second half deficit to beat Philadelphia 102-98 on Thursday night. "Anytime you don't have to play against Allen Iverson, it's a relief for the point guard," Watson said. "He's a guy I watched growing up, a guy I idolized and his determination is second to none." Iverson missed his second consecutive game with a sprained right foot. He did not play in Tuesday's home loss to Toronto and didn't accompany the team to Seattle. Coach Maurice Cheeks said Iverson would not play on Friday in Los Angeles against the Clippers. Without the league's second-leading scorer, the Sixers lost for the fifth time in their last six games. "I thought our guys played extremely hard and their guys came in and made the plays they had to make down the stretch," Cheeks said. The Sixers suffered a fourth-quarter collapse for the second straight game, while Seattle won for the third time in its last four. Against Toronto, Philadelphia was outscored 33-12 in the fourth quarter, and Seattle outscored the Sixers 29-19. Philadelphia fell 4½ games behind New Jersey for the Atlantic Division lead. The Sixers still had chances even without Iverson. Trailing 94-92, Chris Webber missed consecutive short jumpers that could have pulled the 76ers even. After the second miss, Watson ripped the rebound away from Steven Hunter, then found Allen on the wing for a 3-pointer with 54.8 seconds left. John Salmons scored to pull the Sixers to 97-94, and Watson followed by missing a 3-pointer. Watson hustled back on defense and blocked Salmons' layup attempt. Matt Barnes got the rebound and was fouled by Allen, but made just one free throw. Luke Ridnour was fouled with 12.7 seconds left and made both free throws for a 99-95 Seattle lead. Salmons made a 3-pointer with 5.1 seconds left, but Seattle got the ball inbound to Allen, who was fouled and rimmed-out the first free throw before making the second. Out of timeouts, the Sixers tried to throw downcourt, but Rashard Lewis intercepted the pass and got the ball to Allen, who was fouled and made both free throws. "Come the fourth quarter, we buckled down and got the stop and made some good plays offensively," Allen said. "Earl, I don't want to call him a backup point guard because he's just as good as many guards in this league." Watson scored 12 points and had seven assists for Seattle, but it was his defense on Salmons that changed the flow of the game. Philadelphia was nearly perfect starting the second half, scoring points on its first 10 possessions and made eight consecutive shots to take a 73-58 lead. Salmons would post up on the undersized Ridnour, then pass to Webber and Hunter, who had three dunks to start the half. Enter Watson who requested the assignment and kept Salmons under wraps. Seattle then used a 10-2 run to get back within five. "I said 'let me play him one-on-one," Watson said. "He was doing a great job of creating for others." Lewis added 18 points, including a 3-pointer with 3:16 left to put Seattle ahead 92-90. Chris Wilcox had 17 points and his dunk with 3:54 left gave Seattle an 89-88 lead, its first since late in the first quarter. Hunter scored a career-high 20 points and blocked six shots, but was just 4-for-9 from the foul line. Webber scored 20 and had 11 rebounds, but shot just 9 of 26. Andre Iguodala added 17 points, Kyle Korver scored 16 and Salmons had 12. "We go the lead and kind of tightened up and they hit big shots down the stretch and we didn't," Hunter said. "That's the kind of thing where you're missing your star player and he would've been able to bring this one home for us." Johan Petro and Robert Swift both finished with 12 points for Seattle.

Game notes
Sixers G Kevin Ollie played in his first game since March 8. Ollie had been bothered by a sprained right ankle and played 15 minutes and scored four points. ... Seattle reserve F Noel Felix has been named the Continental Basketball Association defensive player of the year. Felix played with the Sioux Falls Skyforce before signing a 10-day contract with the Sonics on March 2.
